T1  - Does Patent Strategy Shape the Long-Run Supply of Public Knowledge? Evidence from Human Genetics
AU  - Huang, Kenneth G.
AU  - Murray, Fiona E.
Y1  - 2009/12/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.47084665
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.47084665
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1193
EP  - 1221
VL  - 52
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Knowledge-based firms seeking competitive advantage often draw on the public knowledge stream (ideas embedded in public commons institutions) as the foundation for private knowledge (ideas firms protect through private intellectual property [IP] institutions). However, understanding of the converse relationship?the impact of private knowledge strategies on public knowledge production?is limited. We examine this question in human genetics, where policy makers debate expanding IP ownership over the human genome. Our difference-in-differences estimates show that gene patents decrease public genetic knowledge, with broader patent scope, private sector ownership, patent thickets, fragmented patent ownership, and a gene's commercial relevance exacerbating their effect.
AB  - Knowledge-based firms seeking competitive advantage often draw on the public knowledge stream (ideas embedded in public commons institutions) as the foundation for private knowledge (ideas firms protect through private intellectual property [IP] institutions). However, understanding of the converse relationship?the impact of private knowledge strategies on public knowledge production?is limited. We examine this question in human genetics, where policy makers debate expanding IP ownership over the human genome. Our difference-in-differences estimates show that gene patents decrease public genetic knowledge, with broader patent scope, private sector ownership, patent thickets, fragmented patent ownership, and a gene's commercial relevance exacerbating their effect.
