TY  - JOUR
T1  - Applying Organizational Research to Public School Reform: The Effects of Teacher Human and Social Capital on Student Performance
AU  - Pil, Frits K.
AU  - Leana, Carrie
Y1  - 2009/12/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2009.47084647
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2009.47084647
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1101
EP  - 1124
VL  - 52
IS  - 6
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We investigated the effects of teacher human and social capital on growth in student performance in a sample of 1,013 teachers organized into 239 grade teams. We found that teacher human capital that is specific to a setting and task, and some indicators of teacher social capital, predicted student performance improvement. At the team level, average educational attainment and horizontal tie strength were significant predictors of student improvement. We provide some evidence that team horizontal tie strength and density moderate the relationship between teacher ability and student performance. Implications of our multilevel analysis for theory, research, and policy are discussed.
AB  - We investigated the effects of teacher human and social capital on growth in student performance in a sample of 1,013 teachers organized into 239 grade teams. We found that teacher human capital that is specific to a setting and task, and some indicators of teacher social capital, predicted student performance improvement. At the team level, average educational attainment and horizontal tie strength were significant predictors of student improvement. We provide some evidence that team horizontal tie strength and density moderate the relationship between teacher ability and student performance. Implications of our multilevel analysis for theory, research, and policy are discussed.
